 the Balsam Orchard with Salih Çelebi Celalzade (d. 1565): First-Person Narrative and Knowledge in Ottoman Egypt -- t14 The Eunuch, a Complete Statesman: Functional Historiography in the Face of Social and Political Precarity -- t15 Reorientation in Worldviews: Milescu and Cantemir -- t16 The Hamidian Visual Archive, 1878–1909: A User’s Manual -- tPart Three: PLACES -- t17 Ottoman Montology: Hazardous Resourcefulness and Uneasy Symbiosis in a Mountain Empire -- t18 Ottoman Mountains: Mobility in a Forbidding Environment -- t19 A Code(x) of His Own: Deacon Mikayēl, Armeno- Turkish, and Creative Conventions of “Collecting” in Seventeenth-Century Kaffa -- t20 On Self and Empire: A Seventeenth-Century First-Person Narrative from the Mughal Domains -- t21 Cabinetmaking for the Sultan: Nineteenth-Century Istanbul in the Life Narratives of German-Speaking Journeymen -- t22 Conjuring Emotions in Nineteenth-Century Istanbul through the Journalistic Writings of Ahmad Faris Al-Shidyaq (1805–87) and Basiretçi Ali (1845?–1910) -- t23 Reşat Ekrem Koçu and İstanbul Ansiklopedisi: Writing on Place -- tPart Four: PROCESSES -- t24 Early Modern Reflections on Bayezid II’s Reign -- t25 The Ottoman Fleet at the Battle of Mississippi: What Videogames Can Teach Us About History -- t26 Continuity and Change in the Ottoman Early Modern Era: An Analysis of ‘Adet-i Kadime and Hâdis -- t27 Between Soldier and Civilian: Janissaries in Seventeenth-Century Istanbul and Aleppo -- t28 Confessionalization and Religious Nonconformity in the Early Modern Ottoman Empire: The Cases of Kizilbash/Alevi and the Sabbatean Communities -- t29 De-a‘yanization: A Black Hole in Ottoman History -- t30 Bitter Triumph of “the Declined” Dynasty? Notions of Universal Monarchy, Caliphate, and World Religions in Comparisons between Sultan Abdulhamid and Emperor Meiji -- tNotes on Contributors -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt would not be an overstatement to say that Cemal Kafadar has transformed the field of Ottoman history. As a result of his pathbreaking books and articles, the field is experiencing a turn within itself as well as recasting its relationship with world history. This volume acts as a tribute to Kafadar and the important interdisciplinary work he has both done and inspired in the field. In line with the intellectual pluralism that Kafadar has cultivated over his career, readers will find a number of articles engaging with a wide range of questions, approaches, perspectives, and sources across Ottoman history. Kafadar's students and friends, individually or in pairs, researched and crafted contributions to this volume with a variety of conceptual premises, theoretical approaches, and interpretive tools to celebrate his thirty years of teaching, research, and mentorship, in addition to the overwhelming generosity of his intellectual and personal engagement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aIstanbul.  aOttoman Empire.  aOttoman History.  aOttoman Studies.  aOttoman literature.1 aAkısık-Karakullukçu, Aslıhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlam, Muzaffar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtiyas, Ekin Tuşalp, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAydin, Cemil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBağcı, Serpil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanbakal, Hülya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasale, Giancarlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDakhlia, Jocelyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v